From  the  antimicrobial  strain  of  Streptomyces  sporoverrucosus  (MTCC11715)  isolated  from  soil samples of Jammu hills two known naphthocoumarins chrysomycin A (1) and B (2) along  with  a  new  naphthocoumarin  chrysomycin  C  (3)  were  isolated  and  characterized.    The  structure of new compound 3 was established by 2D-NMR data. Chrysomycin A (1) and B (2)  were identified by a strategic HPLC-PDA/LCMS and Dictionary of Natural Products (DNP)- based  fast  dereplication.  Additionally,  two  new  naphthocoumarins  chrysomycin  D  and  E  were  identified  using  LCMS,  UV  and  DNP  information.  Chrysomycins  A-C  (1-3)  were  isolated  for  the  first  time  from  Streptomyces  sporoverrucosus  and  were  screened  for  cytotoxicity  in  a  panel  of  cancer  cell  lines  (A549,  Colo205,  PC-3,  MIAPaCa-2,  and  HL-60),  amongst which most potent activity was observed against human leukemia HL-60 cells with  IC50  values  of  0.9,  0.95  and  11  µµµµM,  respectively.  The  mechanistic  studies  indicated  that  chrysomycin  A  (1)  and  B  (2)  at  1  µµµµM  concentration  distorted  cellular  and  nuclear  morphology with significant DNA damage and apoptosis in HL-60 cells.

Historically the nature has been a source for majority of the drugs  which  are  in  use  today.1,  2  Among  various  natural  sources,  plants  have  been  extensively  explored  phytochemically  as  well  as  pharmacologically;  however,  only  a  small  percentage  of  known  microbial  secondary  metabolites  have  been  investigated  for  their  therapeutic  potential.  Thus,  the  microbial  natural  product-based  drug discovery programs needs to become more efficient, starting  with  the  collection  of  samples,  selection  of  strains,  metabolic  expression, genetic exploitation, sample preparation and chemical  dereplication.  ‘Dereplication’  is  an  early  identification  of  known  compounds  in  crude  extracts,  which  prevents  repeated  discovery  and  avoids  unnecessary  efforts  on  extensive  spectroscopic

The  Streptomyces  genus  has  been  a  source  for  large  number  of  antibiotics,  antitumor  and  immunosuppressant  natural  products.12- 14 Around two-third of all known natural antibiotics are produced  by  these  bacteria.13  Herein,  we  report  isolation  of  three  cytotoxic  naphthocoumarins  chrysomycin  A-C  (1-3,  Figure  1)  from  Streptomyces sporoverrucosus (MTCC11715) strain isolated from  the soil samples collected from Jammu Hill regions. Additionally,  two  more  new  naphthocoumarins  chrysomycin  D  (4)  and  E  (5)  were identified using LCMS/ UV/ DNP information.  Figure  1  Chemical  structures  of  chrysomycins  A-C  (1-3).  COSY  and HBMC correlations for chrysomycin C (3) are also shown.  [journal], [year], [vol], 00–00  |  1

During  our  investigations  on  soil  samples  collected  from  Jammu  hill  regions  (Panchari,  Udhumpur,  India),  large  number  of  actinomycetes  (>200)  were  isolated.  The  isolated  actinomycetes  were  screened  for  antimicrobial  activity  against  a  panel  of  microbes  including  Escherchia  coli,  Pseudomonas  aeruginosa,  Staphylococcus  aureus,  Micrococcus  luteus,  Bacillus  subtilis  and  Candida  albicans  by  agar  diffusion  method.  The  actinomycete  strain  IIIMA2123,  which  showed  promising  inhibition  zone  against S. aureus (20 mm), M. luteus (30 mm), B. subtilis (18 mm)  and  C.  albicans  (15  mm)  was  selected  for  isolation  of  secondary  metabolites.  The  soil  isolate  of  actinomycete  strain  (IIIMA2123)  was  found  to  be  filamentous,  gram-positive,  spore-forming  bacteria and has been identified as Streptomyces sporoverrucosus  by  16s  rDNA  methodology.  For  16s  rDNA  identification,  the  genomic DNA of the pure culture was isolated. The ~1.4kb rDNA  fragment was amplified using high–fidelity PCR polymerase. The  PCR  product  was  sequenced  bi-directional  using  the  forward,  reverse  and  internal  primers.  The  percentage  identity  of  this  new  bacterial strain (IIIMA-2123) with  the most similar bacteria strain  was 99.7% (Streptomyces sporoverrucosus  (T) NRRL B-16379T;  Gene  bank  entry:  DQ442544).  This  microbial  stain  (IIIMA2123)  has  been  deposited  in  a  repository  of  Microbial  type  Culture  Collections & Gene bank (MTCC) at IMTECH Chandigarh,

Gene  bank  entry:  DQ442544).  This  microbial  stain  (IIIMA2123)  has  been  deposited  in  a  repository  of  Microbial  type  Culture  Collections & Gene bank (MTCC) at IMTECH Chandigarh, India  and  assigned  the  accession  no.  MTCC11715.  The  rDNA  1376bp  sequences  gb- admin@ncbi.nlm.nih.gov  (GeneBank accession no. KC855264).

The  Streptomyces  sporoverrucosus  (MTCC11715)  was  then  grown in 7L fermentor. The fermentor broth was passed through  HP20 resin and the adsorbed material was eluted with methanol:  water  (8:  2)  to  get  crude  extract,  which  was  subjected  to  the  bioassay-guided  fractionation  (for  cytotoxicity)  using  silica-gel  column chromatography. The intense yellow colored band, eluted  at  4%  MeOH/CHCl3  displayed  promising  cytotoxicity  in  A549  (lung),  Colo205  (colon),  MIAPaCa-2  (pancreatic)  and  HL-60  (leukemia)  cells.  The  identification  of  secondary  metabolites  in  the  active  fraction  was  performed  using  HPLC-PDA/MS  based  dereplication strategy as depicted in Figure 2. Simultaneously,  a  parallel  LCMS  protocol  was  developed to  get  corresponding  masses  for  these  three  major  peaks  and  also  to  identify more metabolites. The LCMS chromatogram is shown in  Figure 4, which provided masses of all three peaks of Figure 3 as  well  as  showed  identification  two  more  metabolites  (at  tR  53.3  and 58.9 min) of similar chromophore with new masses.

The  LC-ESIMS  chromatogram  displayed  masses  m/z  525,  523,  495,  507  and  509  [M-H]-  for  peaks  appearing  at  tR  53.3,  58.9,  65.0, 70.8 and 73.1 min, respectively. The information related to  biological  (no  compound was reported from this species) and the mass and UV  profile  of  five  compounds  was  then  used  as  input  data  in  Dictionary of Natural Product for rapid dereplication. For one of  the  major  peak  which  is  eluted  at  tR  65.0  min  (m/z  495  [M-H]  -  and λmax of 244 nm), the input information: (1) Biological source:  Streptomyces.  (2)  Accurate  mass  range:  496.000  to 496.999  and  (3)  UV  maxima:  244  nm  was  used  in  DNP  database.  The  snapshot  of  search  results  of  DNP  database  is  shown  in  section  S14  of  ESI.  It  is  noteworthy  to  mention  that  >6000  compounds  are reported from genus Streptomyces. This list was then filtered  by  applying  mass  range  (496.000  to  496.999)  to  get  list  of  18  compounds,  which  was  again  filtered  by  applying  UV  maxima  (244 nm) to get list of 2 compounds; chrysomycin B (2) and 18- hydroxynapyradiomycin A1. The possibility of second compound  was ruled out because of its physical property as yellow oil while  our  compound  was  solid  (later  we  have  isolated  this  compound  for  biological  screening).  Thus,  the  peak  at  tR  65.0  min  was  identified  as  chrysomycin  B  (2,  also  known  as  chrysomycin  M;  virenomycin

compound  for  biological  screening).  Thus,  the  peak  at  tR  65.0  min  was  identified  as  chrysomycin  B  (2,  also  known  as  chrysomycin  M;  virenomycin  M  and  albacarcin  M  as  its  epimer),  a  compound  which  was  first  identified  in 1954  as  a  antibacterial  substance,15  and  later  its  anticancer  activity  was  reported.16,  17  Further,  we  carried out a similarity search of chrysomycin B by substructure  search  (http://www.pharmaceutical- bioinformatics.de/streptomedb)13  and  PubChem  search  engine.  This search showed   gilvocarcin  M, gilvocarcin  A, chrysomycin  A,  gilvocarcin  E,  gilvocarcin  V,  NSC348115  and  ravidomycine  type  C-glycoside  antibiotics  which  are  popular  for  their  potent  cytotoxic  activity  in  variety  of  cell  lines  (PubChembioassay:  http://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/assay/  assay)    and  inhibition  of  human  toposiomerase  II.18  At  this  level,  we  came  to  know  that  the  fraction  may  contain  either  of  these  antibiotics,  which  was  supported  by  their  chromophore  similarity  as  indicated  in  UV  spectrum and potent biological activity of the fraction. Next, the  mass and UV data of another major peak eluted at 70.8 min (m/z  507  [M-H]-,  UVmax  244/246  nm)  was  processed  in  a  similar  manner, which led to its identification as chrysomycin A (1, also  known as chrysomycin V; virenomycin V).

The  third  major  peak  eluted  at  tR  73.1  min  displaying  [M-H]-  at  m/z 509 was identified as a new compound of the same chemical  class, with a mass difference of 2 units compared to chrysomycin  A (1), which indicated that it comprises ethyl group in the place  of vinyl group. Thus, the LCMS and DNP information indicated the presence of  two known and three new chrysomycin class of compounds. This  class  of  compounds  are  known  to  possess  promising  anticancer  activities,19-28  thus  we  proceeded  further  to  isolate,  characterize  and  evaluate  anticancer  activity  of  these  identified  compounds. The  position  of    CH2  was  confirmed  by  HMBC  spectra wherein the CH2 protons showed key correlations with C- 8 (147.8 ppm), C-9 (118.4 ppm) and CH3 (15.21 ppm) (Figure 1).  Thus,  the  structure  of  3  was  confirmed  as  the  analog  of  chrysomycin  A  in  which  vinyl  moiety  is  replaced  with  ethyl  moiety, and  we named this new  structure as chrysomycin C (3). Since the available material was insufficient for isolation and full  characterization  of  two  additional  minor  compounds;  we  used  HPLC-PDA/LCMS-DNP-based  identification  method  in  crude  material. The peak eluted at tR 53.3 min displayed [M-H]- peak at  m/z  525  and  similar  UV  pattern  (Figure  4d-e).  The  another  peak  which was eluted at tR 58.9 min displayed mass m/z 523.1 [M-H]-  and  again  similar  UV  pattern  (Figure  4f-g).  To  identify  probable  structures of these metabolites, we carefully analyzed the available  literature  information  from  DNP.  This  analysis  indicated  that  the  C-glycoside antibiotics are classified into three classes on the basis  of linked sugar viz. gilvocarcin type (furanose), chrysomycin type  (pyranose)  and  ravidomycin  type  (pyranosamine),  however  the  basic  naphthocoumarin  skeleton  remains  unchanged  in  all  three  classes. Therefore, we used naphthocoumarin core for substructure  tetracyclic  search  naphthocoumarin  skeleton  showed  27  compounds  which  belongs  to  chrysomycin,  givocarcin,  and  ravidomycin  type  of  compounds  (for  DNP  screenshot,  see  section  S15  of  ESI). 526 for tR 53.3; and mass 524 for tR 58.9 min) is not present and  thus these are presumed to be new structures. Further, the careful  structural  analysis  of  all  naturally  occurring  napthocoumarin  linked C-glycoside antibiotics indicated that five different types of  substitutions at C-8 position are reported (viz. methyl, vinyl, ethyl,  epoxide and hydroxyl containing moieties). The methyl, vinyl and  ethyl functionalities are frequently reported; however the hydroxyl  containing side chain is only reported in gilvocarcin HE (-CHOH- CH3 at C-8)31 and ravidomycin antibiotic SS-50408D. The epoxide  chain  is  reported  once  in  ravidomycin  analog  (DNP  database:  www.chemnetbase.com). Thus, based on the UV and MS data and  careful  analysis  of  this  class  of  known  compounds,  the  structures  of  peaks  at  tR  53.3  and 58.9  min  are  proposed  as  chrysomycin  C  analogs  in  which  the  8-ethyl  moiety  has  been  modified  as  (2- hydroxy)ethyl  and  epoxide,  respectively.  We  named  these  two  identified  compounds  as  chrysomycin  D  and  E,  respectively.  Furthermore, these compounds are biogenetically feasible.30-35

The  isolated  three  compounds  chrysomycins  A-C  (1-3)  were  screened  for  antiproliferative  activity  in  a  panel  of  cancer  cell  lines  viz.  A549,  Colo205,  PC-3,  MIAPaCa-2,  and  HL-60.36  A  tetrazolium  based  calorimetric  cytotoxicity  assay  was  used  to  evaluate  the  cytotoxicity  of  compounds  in  different  cancer  cell  lines  after  48  h.  The  crude  fraction  displayed  cytotoxicity  in  all  cancer cell lines with IC50 in the range of 0.05-4 µg/ml; and the  most potent activity was observed in HL-60 leukemia cells (IC50  0.05  µg/ml).  Chrysomycins  A-C  (1-3)  also  showed  cytotoxicity  in  all  cell  lines,  however  most  potent  activity  was  observed  in  leukemia  cells,  with  IC50  values  of  0.95,  0.9  and  11  µM,  respectively  (Table  2).  Furthermore,  chrysomycin  B  (2)  also  displayed promising  cytotoxicity in lung cancer A549 cells with  IC50 value of 2 µM (Table 2).  Table 2. Further the mechanistic investigations of chrysomycins A-C (1-3)  in HL-60 cells was carried out. The effect of chrysomycins A-C  (1-3) on  the  DNA  damage  and  apoptosis  was  investigated  using  cell  cycle  analysis.37  The  human  leukemia  HL-60  cells  were  treated  with  compounds  1-3  at  1,  3  and  5  µM  for  24  h.  These  compounds  exhibited  a  concentration-dependent  increase  in  hypo-diploid  sub-G0  DNA  fraction  (<2nDNA),  which  indicated  apoptotic  population  (Figure  5).  Compound  1  (chrysomycin  A)  was found to be most active in terms of degree of DNA damage  and  apoptosis  induction  in  HL-60  cells.  Compound  1  at  1  µM  showed 72% Sub G0 DNA apoptotic fraction, while control cells  showed  around  2%  sub-G0  DNA  population.  Compound  3  (chrysomycin  C)  was  least  active  and  did  not  induce  DNA  damage significantly even at 5 µM concentration. Figure  5.    Cell  cycle  analysis  of  human  leukemia  HL-60  cells  treated with indicated compounds for 24 h. Cells were exposed to  different concentrations of compounds for 24 h and stained with PI  to determine DNA fluorescence. Cell cycle phase distribution were  analysed by modfit software and hypodiploid population (Sub G0,  <2n  DNA)  were  accounted  as  apoptotic  population.  Data  are  representative of  one of the two similar experiments.  The  effect  of  compounds  1-3  on  the  cellular  and  nuclear  morphology  of  HL-60  cells  was  also  investigated.38  The  HL-60  cells  were  treated  with  compounds  1,  2  and  3  at  three  concentrations  (1,  3  and  5  µM)  for  24  h  and  the  damaged  cells  with  blebs,  condensed  nuclei  and  apoptotic  bodies  were  visualized  under  fluorescence  and  phase  contrast  microscope.  Compounds  1  and  2  showed  significant  induction  in  number  of  condensed  nuclei  and  apoptotic  bodies  formation,  which  is  indicated by white arrows, while the nuclei of untreated cells are  round  and  regular  in  shape  (Figure  6  and  7).  The  number  of  apoptotic  bodies  was  found  to  be  increased  with  the  increase  in  concentration of compounds 1 and 2 in HL-60 cells. Isolation of actinomycetes cultures.  The  soils  samples  for  isolation  of  actinomycetes  were  collected  during the period of June to November from 10-15 cm deep soil  of  Jammu  region  (Panchari  Udhumpur;  J  &  K,  India).  All  samples  were  air  died,  crushed  and  sieved  through  sterilized  100U mesh. The sieved soil samples were used  for the isolation  of  actinomycetes.  The  1.0  g  of  the  sieved  soil  sample  was  suspended in sterilized 10 ml physiological solution (NaCl   5.0  g/l) / dH2O followed by incubation on a orbital shaker at 200 rpm  (28  ºC)  for  30  minutes.  Soil  particles  were  allowed  to  settle  followed by plating on MBS (starch 10 g/l, calcium chloride 0.5  g/l,  sodium  chloride  1.0  g/l,  diammonium  sulphate  0.5  g/l,  magnesium sulphate 1 g/l, agar 25 g/l, pH 7.2) and CYPS (casein:  10.0 g/l, starch 10 g/l,  yeast  extract 1.0 g/l, peptone 1.0 g/l, and  Agar  20  g/l,    pH  7.2  before  agar  addition)  medium  by  various  serial  dilutions.  The  percentage  of  actinomycetes  was  maximum  in MBS medium containing salts with starch as carbon source in  comparison  with  CYPS  medium  which  contains  yeast  and  peptone as nitrogen sources.  Selection of actinomycetes cultures.

Actinomycetes isolated  from MBS and CYPS were incubated at  28  °C  for  7  days  on  agar  media,  the  morphologically  different  types  of  colonies  were  picked  up  and  separately  preserved  in  CYPS.  More than two hundred actinomycetes were isolated from  soil  samples  collected  from  Panchari  area.
